{#def title="Minds", body_class="bg-transparent text-primary font-sans antialiased", body_style="", body_attrs="", head="", scripts="", boot_state=None #}
{#
  Base variant for edge-to-edge transparent surfaces loaded into the shared
  overlay WebContentsView: the overlay host and the modal pages it hosts
  (workspace menu / inbox / help / sign-in), plus any future overlay surface.

  The contract these pages share: they paint fixed full-viewport layers
  (their own dim backdrop or measured bubbles), never scroll at the document
  level, and must paint all the way to the window's right edge. That last
  part is why this wrapper exists -- it pins ``no-scrollbar-gutter`` on the
  html element so the global ``scrollbar-gutter: stable`` rule (app.css)
  cannot reserve a classic-scrollbar gutter that nothing paints, which
  clipped tooltips mid-label and left modal dim backdrops short of the
  window edge. New overlay surfaces get that opt-out by wrapping in this
  component instead of remembering an html_class.

  The chrome titlebar page is edge-to-edge too but NOT a transparent
  overlay (it paints the titlebar background), so it stays on Base with an
  explicit ``html_class="no-scrollbar-gutter"``.

  Args mirror Base (title / body_style / body_attrs / head / scripts);
  ``body_class`` defaults to the shared transparent overlay body.

  Every overlay surface also loads the mithril component bundle
  (window.MindsUI) ahead of the page's own scripts: overlay modal pages are
  separate documents, so they cannot rely on the chrome shell's copy of the
  tag. Classic (not deferred) so inline page scripts can mount immediately.
#}
{% set _scripts %}
<script src="/_static/dist/chrome.bundle.js"></script>
{{ scripts }}
{% endset %}
<Base title={{ title }}
      html_class="no-scrollbar-gutter"
      body_class={{ body_class }}
      body_style={{ body_style }}
      body_attrs={{ body_attrs }}
      head={{ head }}
      scripts={{ _scripts }}>
  {#- ``boot_state`` (a JSON-ready dict) renders the #minds-boot-state island
     MindsUI mount functions parse. Overlay pages are standalone documents (no
     ChromeShell / swap engine), so the island simply precedes the content. -#}
  {%- if boot_state is not none %}
  <script type="application/json" id="minds-boot-state">{{ boot_state | tojson }}</script>
  {%- endif %}
  {{- content -}}
</Base>
